export const WORLD_CONTENT_VERSION = 103;  // LAKES STAMP INTO THE TILE RASTER. Hydrology lakes (filled basins ABOVE sea level ŌĆö `waterType === Lake`) were never written into `tile.type`: the elevation-classified tile under a drawn lake said grass/forest/mountain, so every consumer gating on the raster ŌĆö brushes, building placer, road walker, pathfinding, settlement growth ŌĆö treated the lake bed as dry, walkable, buildable land while the renderer painted standing water over it (the WCV-98 water-habitat sweep cleaned the flora SYMPTOM downstream; the raster kept lying, and the placement/routing consumers still read it). Lake cells now stamp `water` + walkable:false in the SAME hydrologyŌåÆtile pass that stamps rivers, with the render mask's own ocean > lake > river precedence (a river run threading the basin reads lake, exactly as drawn). The habitat sweep stays ŌĆö tiles and drawn water still diverge where roads carve bridge/dirt over the channel, by design. TWO coupled consequences of lakes finally being real to tile-readers: (a) the road walker now prices STANDING water (lake/deep/ocean) at `standingWaterCost` (45/cell) vs the bridgeable `bridgeCost` (5/cell) for rivers + the shallow fringe ŌĆö you bridge a river, you go AROUND a lake, only a short neck earns a causeway (before the stamp the walker saw a lake bed as dry land and ran roads across the drawn water); (b) irrigation ditches drink from `getRenderWaterMask` (the drawn water) rather than the tile raster, so a field beside a bridged reach still finds its source. Tile types/walkability + road routes change on every seed with an inland basin ŌĆö settlements, roads and vegetation re-site around real shorelines ŌćÆ discard older autosaves. KNOWN FOLLOW-UP: authored POIs generated on a foreign gen-seed's terrain can land IN a lake (settlement types must be dry; lake/swamp/port POIs legitimately want water) ŌĆö type-aware POI water-anchoring is its own round. (prev 102) ROAD A*/DRAWING FIX ROUND ŌĆö metre-true routing + honest centerline reconciliation. (1) The walker's grade model is now PHYSICAL rise/run (`reliefM`/`METRES_PER_TILE`; per-class envelope 8/12/18/25 % with a QUADRATIC over-grade penalty) ŌĆö the old normalised units meant 84ŌĆō264 % tolerated grade at default relief, so hilly seeds re-route onto honest gentler lines (worst walked grade 1.66ŌåÆ1.37 @777, 1.49ŌåÆ0.91 @999); step grades read the bilinear midpoint (sub-tile), and the carve's grade line samples `heightMetresBilinearAt` at the true fractional centerline (plan and carve see the renderer's surface). (2) Plain-smoothing bows beyond the reconcile margin are PINNED back through the walked cells (`edge.pins`, persisted; `reconcileCenterlineBows` + `reconcileCenterlineLegality`) ŌĆö kills both the doubled "lens" roads and the ribbon sagging up to 2 tiles onto rock/water the router avoided (ribbon-illegal cells 23ŌĆō55/seed ŌåÆ 0; new whole-line `roads.ribbon-legal` error clause). (3) `repairConnectionSplits` connectors become REAL road edges (centerline/carve/ribbon), and a visibility reconcile clears `baseType` on ribbon-orphaned road tiles ŌĆö the INVISIBLE walkable-grass-road class ŌåÆ 0. (4) Degree-2 shared nodes get cross-edge tangent fillets (no more free-standing ~90┬░ hairpin hooks); `orthogonalize`'s both-bad fallback prefers the bridgeable water cell. Road routes/tiles/carves shift on most seeds ŌćÆ discard older autosaves. (prev 101) TIMBER BRIDGES GET THEIR CARPENTRY (the parapet-rails round, proven against 5 TTI references). Three coupled changes to how `buildBridgeObject` composes a crossing: (1) OPEN POST-AND-RAIL PARAPETS ŌĆö the deck part grows `parapet:'rails'` (top handrail + mid rail per side riding the camber per segment, square posts stationed every ~1.8 m whose heads stand PROUD of the top rail ŌĆö the profile every wooden TTI reference draws); the default timber-arch class now uses it, masonry keeps the solid `'both'` walls, log-plank has none. (2) MULTI-BAY TIMBER = A HUMP